kb:partial-facts
    pred:description "Human-in-the-loop completion of the F31 local-orchestration loop. When a local sub-agent is uncertain about the OBJECT of a fact it emits a PARTIAL FACT — subject + predicate known, object left as a loose end — together with its question, instead of guessing or spending Opus tokens to resolve it. In the review screen the reviewer FILLS the object rather than editing a guessed value: a search-while-typing picker over existing entities (reusing the RelationBuilder node-list pattern), or create-new (new entity IRI via labelToIri, or a plain text value). Accept is gated until the object is filled. On confirm the resolved fact flows BACK to the waiting sub-agent via knowledge.answers.jsonl in the workspace, so it can resume — closing the loop. Model: Statement gains optional needsObject + question fields (types.ts); pending JSONL lines may omit `object` (carrying a `question`) to denote a partial fact; drainAndImportPending maps these to needsObject statements; kb entityChoices() supplies the picker; workspace recordAnswer() appends the resolved triple to knowledge.answers.jsonl. UI in DiffEntry.svelte. Depends on F31 (Opus + local sub-agents + kb_add_note questions). SHIPPED 2026-07-07: demonstrated end-to-end — local agent hoisted a partial fact (embedding-model quantization ?), human filled it in the review picker as a new entity, the answer flowed back via knowledge.answers.jsonl, and the waiting agent resumed; two bugs found in testing and fixed (computeDiff crashed on placeholder objects; swipe-accept could confirm an unfilled ?)." ;
    pred:depends-on kb:local-model-bench ;
    pred:relates-to kb:review-workbench ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:feature-id "F32" ;
    rdfs:label "Partial Facts & Answer-Flow-Back" ;
    pred:has-status "functional" ;
    pred:in-dev "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date .

kb:review-anchored-generation
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:relates-to kb:change-notes ;
    pred:depends-on kb:context-compression ;
    pred:principle "Not all knowledge compresses to clean triples (tone, hedges, the 'because'). That irreducible nuance is what change-notes hold: canonical facts (fully regenerable) + human prose (the nuance that can't be re-derived)." ;
    rdfs:label "Review-Anchored Generation" ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:principle "The graph of reviewed facts is the scarce, canonical input; text (docs, pages, prose) is a cheap, disposable, context-tailored OUTPUT generated from it. Store and review facts, not prose." ;
    pred:principle "Every generated sentence MUST trace back to a confirmed triple. Generation that invents a claim not in the graph reintroduces hallucination at the render step — the inversion only works married to grounded generation + provenance (ETHICS_PREAMBLE, Shelly's 'only from your triples')." ;
    pred:description "Make the RAG-inversion the explicit architecture thesis and hold the system to it: one reviewed fact renders to a tooltip, a paragraph, a warning, a page, a PR description — near-infinite surface, one reviewed source. Builds on context-compression (F25, the compress pipeline) and graph-publishing (F27, graph -> pages); the irreducible-nuance case is change-notes (F44). The moat is the grounding constraint, not the generation." ;
    pred:feature-id "F51" .

kb:deep-testing
    pred:relates-to kb:release-pipeline ;
    pred:in-dev "2026-07-09"^^xsd:date ;
    pred:has-status "scaffolded" ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:feature-id "F34" ;
    rdfs:label "Deep Testing & Living Coverage" ;
    pred:description "PHASE 1 SHIPPED (2026-07-09): offline exhaustive button crawler — scripts/offline/button-crawl.ts (npm run test:crawl). Clicks every interactive element on every route and, per click, records crashes (console/page errors), blank screens (solid-fill pixel artifact via tests/visual/vision-local), SILENT NO-OPS (nothing observable changed — URL / node count / graph id / open panels / title / visible-text hash; the class the docs-hub leap regression fell into, which a crash-only crawler misses), and sub-44px touch targets. Resets to the route before each click for deterministic per-click state. Offline-first: pixel/DOM/touch checks are pure local JS (no Ollama/Opus); findings queued to knowledge.pending.jsonl for review. TIED TO THE GRAPH: the crawl also emits a TestWorkflow -> TestStep STORY graph (tests/visual/button-crawl.ttl — one workflow per route, one step per click, each carrying its screenshot via kmeta:gif and a kpred:result verdict + kpred:violates rubric citations), so results are reviewable in-app as an ordered story rather than a JSON dump (same schema as the navigation-sweep story; written to a sibling file so it never clobbers the separately-generated visual-tests.ttl). NEXT: VLM visual scoring of screenshots against kb:web-uiux-rubric across the device matrix (phase 2); a persistent-context / warm-service-worker pass to catch stale-cache regressions fresh contexts never reproduce (phase 3); Opus authoring new path specs from coverage gaps (phase 4). --- FULL DESIGN: An OFFLINE, ever-growing use-case test system distinct from the fast per-build suite. (1) Deep tests are PREDETERMINED end-user PATHS through the web app, run LOCALLY on demand — not on every build; the per-build suite stays fast (unit + smoke). (2) Two evaluation dimensions beyond pass/fail: a VISUAL surface (each path is captured across a DEVICE MATRIX via Playwright device descriptors — phones + tablets: iPhone 15, Pixel 7, iPad Pro 11 are already configured in playwright.config.ts as touch-emulated projects, extensible to more; a local VLM then scores the per-device screenshots against the Web/Mobile UI-UX Rubric, so responsive/touch guidelines are checked at real viewport sizes — scalable emulation that complements spot-checks on physical iPhone/iPad) and a TEXT/output-consumption surface (generated answer/output quality — leads with the conclusion, scannable, grounded). (3) The rubric is a graph: reckons-workspace design-principles graph (kb:web-uiux-rubric) — testable guidelines grounded in core design principles; every finding CITES the violated guideline (kpred:derives-from -> core principle). Mobile-tagged guidelines gate the responsive work. (4) Opus orchestration periodically ANALYZES coverage, finds GAPS, and authors new path specs at various times (not every build); paths are graph entities so the library grows. (5) Novel user workflows: the app transparently benches and KINDLY ASKS the user to opt in to contributing their real workflow as a new test path (consent-based, never covert). (6) Runs as an offline procedure (scripts/offline/), emitting gaps + rubric violations as pending questions for review in Reckons.AI. Builds on visual-testing (VLM gate) and relates to the release pipeline's developer gate. Consumes the offline-first / Opus-orchestrates-online model." ;
    pred:depends-on kb:visual-testing .

