kb:control-model
    pred:relates-to kb:cross-kb-alignment ;
    pred:description "The enforced boundary of what an agent may write directly (plan/code) vs. only propose (facts, pending review), with alignment reframed as a discrepancy detector and cross-graph divergence treated as a question. The key differentiating feature. Relates to cross-Graph alignment (F16), git-analysis (F24), the review workflow, change-notes (F44), and the release pipeline (F33)." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:change-notes ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:principle "Divergence between two graphs is often intentional FOCUS, not drift. A 'misalignment' is a question ('these disagree — on purpose?'), never an auto-reconcile." ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:principle "The human holds the fact-edit right. Agents PROPOSE (pending) on knowledge/facts and may edit plan/code/roadmap TTL directly — that boundary is control, and today it is convention, not enforcement. Make it a wall: fact-level agent writes go through review." ;
    pred:principle "Alignment is a TRIGGER for human review, not a goal to optimize. The instant an agent can edit the graph to raise its own alignment score, the score measures nothing (Goodhart). Alignment must summon a human at a discrepancy; it must never auto-resolve or let an agent self-serve." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:release-pipeline ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:feature-id "F52" ;
    pred:principle "Deliver control seamlessly: keep traditional outputs (web pages, markdown) so switching cost from the traditional method to the knowledge-graph method is near zero. Documentation is one render of the knowledge; implementation accuracy and speed is another." ;
    rdfs:label "Control Model — the agent-edit boundary" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:git-analysis .

