kb:spatial-force-layout
    pred:feature-id "F59" ;
    pred:has-status "speculative" ;
    rdfs:label "Spatial / map force layout" ;
    pred:open-question "Earth model: how much geodesy is worth it (great-circle distance + a globe mesh) vs. a simple projected plane for small extents? Solar-system / space scale is a stretch goal." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:entity-types ;
    pred:description "Add a 'map' / 'place' force mode alongside the existing ones. Nodes with location facts are positioned by their coordinates; nodes without stay related-but-loose (or hidden) so mixed graphs still read. The mode DISPLAYS physical distance (e.g. the 327 mi / 5h drives in the starter graph) rather than spring-relation distance. Scale-aware: GPS is assumed to be on Earth's surface, so render with Earth's curvature + scale; astronomical coordinates place nodes in space (solar-system scale). Also the umbrella for improving how the starter graph reads across ALL force modes (it exercises timeline via scheduled-at/ends-at, type via its custom types, hub via people<->options, and now map via coordinates)." ;
    pred:principle "Some concepts are best seen by RELATION (the current force modes); others by LOCATION. A place with GPS coordinates has a true position — the graph should be able to honour it, and show real physical distance, without forcing every other node onto a map." ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:open-question "Portable plain-text location format — UNDECIDED. Must be plain text and easily portable. Accept multiple input formats (decimal lat/lon, DMS, geo: URIs, maybe WKT/GeoJSON-as-text) and normalise; the graph assumes bare GPS = Earth surface. Which canonical predicate(s) — reuse p:coordinates, or a typed geo predicate?" .

