kb:meta-visual-generation
    pred:relates-to kb:wf-reckon ;
    pred:has-status "speculative" ;
    pred:feature-id "F58" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:review-anchored-generation ;
    pred:principle "The graph is the brief. The FACTS and the RELATIONSHIPS between an entity's visual assets are the detailed description that drives the generation — a red hex on a node recolors its image; two node images with a 'combine' relationship (or a prompt) merge into one; a subgraph of GLBs assembles into a scene." ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    rdfs:label "Meta Visual Asset Generation" ;
    pred:principle "Creative generation does NOT need the full Situation-Target-Proposal loop. STP is for grounded decisions; making an asset is expression. So generation offers a single free-form prompt AND the option to drop STP prompting entirely for more variety — while still injecting the relevant graph facts as context." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:int-meshy ;
    pred:description "Collage/compose everything a graph (or selected subgraph) holds — source images, GLB models, 2D icons, preview images — plus the facts and inter-asset relationships, into ONE output asset. Enhanced Reckoning becomes 'a generation of some kind': the output can be a picture, a PDF, or a 3D file rather than a text proposal. Needs a NEW generation backend (no text/image->image capability exists today; 3D exists via Meshy text-to-3d). Local 3D generation feasibility is unknown — flagged for research; Meshy.AI is the likely near-term path to function." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:entity-types .

kb:integration-plugin-sdk
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:relates-to kb:int-game-engine ;
    pred:relates-to kb:gen-orchestration ;
    pred:feature-id "F61" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:gp-gitlab ;
    rdfs:label "Integration Plugin SDK" ;
    pred:principle "The integration count is the product surface — it must scale by CONVENTION, not bespoke wiring each time. Separate integrations behind one plug-in contract so a new one is 'implement the interface + register', and the app discovers capabilities generically." ;
    pred:description "DEVELOPMENT PROCESS (to be documented as part of this): (1) scaffold from an integration template; (2) implement the capability interface(s); (3) declare config schema + auth; (4) register the plug-in; (5) capability-level tests against a fake backend (the drive-sync fake-Drive test is the model); (6) a Settings→Integrations entry renders automatically from the config schema. Documented in the Architecture KB, not a new docs/*.md (TTL-first policy)." ;
    pred:description "Architecturally separate the integrations (today ad-hoc under src/lib/integrations/<company>/) behind a plug-in SDK: a typed contract each integration implements — id/label, declared CAPABILITIES (ingest / sync / storage / generation / auth), a config schema (keys, endpoints) that renders its own Settings UI, an auth lifecycle, and typed entry points. A registry discovers plug-ins and the app drives them by capability rather than by name. The LLM provider backends (claude/openai/gemini/ollama/wasm/…, already per-task-selectable) are the pattern to generalise across ALL integration kinds. Enables: swap GitHub<->GitLab (F55.3), plug-in asset-gen tools (F58.8 orchestration), a game-engine plug-in (F59.1), and cloud-storage providers (F55.2) without touching the core." ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:has-status "speculative" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:gp-cloud-storage ;
    pred:relates-to kb:llm-providers .

