kb:question-context-pages
    rdfs:label "Triple-Question Context Pages" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:feature-id "F46" ;
    pred:description "An OPTIONAL short context/summary page attached to a specific pending triple or '? question' fact, to give the reviewer what they need to decide. MOTIVATION: the Review tab surfaces partial facts needing an answer (F32 — incoming.needsObject, the 'questions only' filter in routes/(app)/review/+page.svelte), but a bare subject-predicate-? is often not enough context to accept/answer/reject confidently. DESIGN (reuses F27 + F44): the page is a WebPage-like node authored in Sveltia (content/*.md <-> graph round-trip), linked to the question via kpred:context-for -> [the statement/question id or subject IRI], rendered inline in the review card as an expandable summary (excerpt in graph, long-form in the .md). Content can be human-written OR drafted by Shelly grounded in the graph (kb_generate_page / kb_entity_markdown / kb_compress) then edited. Distinct from the answer itself (knowledge.answers.jsonl) — this is decision-support context, not the decision. Kept optional and lightweight so most questions need none. More urgent than F44's change-note use because it unblocks review throughput directly. Relates to F32 partial facts, F44 change notes, and F27 publishing." ;
    pred:relates-to kb:change-notes ;
    pred:relates-to kb:partial-facts ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> .

kb:google-drive-sync
    pred:has-status "scaffolded" ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:depends-on kb:workspace-sync ;
    rdfs:label "Google Drive Sync" ;
    pred:feature-id "F6" ;
    pred:description "OAuth flow and file listing implemented. Auto-sync on mutation not wired." .

kb:graph-as-navigation
    pred:relates-to kb:question-context-pages ;
    pred:description "Make published pages first-class citizens of the graph so the graph itself is the site map. PARTS: (1) WebPage nodes (ktype:WebPage, F27) RENDER as graph nodes — visible alongside concepts, distinguishable (icon/type), selectable. (2) In-graph site structure: define a LANDING/home page and navigation to SUBPAGES as graph edges (reuse skos:broader for parent/child + nav:next/prev for sequence, the same hierarchy vocabulary the hnav trees use), created and rearranged in the graph. (3) LIGHT-FORCE nav edges — CRITICAL: page/nav edges must carry a much lower force-directed spring weight than concept edges, because a nav hub connected to many published pages (or pages linked across every concept) would otherwise collapse/warp the main graph shape. Introduce per-edge-kind force weights (concept edges normal; page/nav edges very light, or excluded from the main force pass and laid out in a secondary/orbit pass) so adding the whole published site never distorts the knowledge layout. (4) In-graph PAGE METADATA editing: edit slug, section, template, status, title from the node panel (writes the urn:kbase:page/* triples; round-trips via F27 site-export + md-align). (5) Publishing map: from any concept, see which pages reference/derive from it and jump to them; from a page node, open the published /docs URL. Builds on F27 graph publishing and relates to F46 (question-context pages, another in-graph page attach), the 2D/3D graph (per-edge force weights), and the /docs route." ;
    pred:feature-id "F49" ;
    pred:principle "The graph is the PRIMARY navigation of what pages are published and where they're accessed — not a separate site-map UI. Publishing structure lives in, and is edited from, the graph." ;
    pred:has-status "planned" ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:relates-to kb:knowledge-graph ;
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    rdfs:label "Graph-as-Site-Navigation" .

kb:arrange-layout-builder
    pred:description "Give the arrange mode a VERTICAL-SCROLL, FULL-SCREEN mode: instead of a fixed canvas grid, nodes flow top-to-bottom in a scrollable column, and can be grouped horizontally (side-by-side) to form rows. You accomplish both a vertical layout (stacked sections) and a horizontal layout (columns within a row) by arranging + ordering. That arrangement is captured on the nodes (order + row/column grouping, extending the existing nodeOrder / hnav ordering) and maps to the published page's block structure. Bridges F27 graph-publishing (WebPage nodes -> content/*.md) and F55.4 custom pages: the arrange canvas becomes a lightweight page-layout builder where blocks are graph nodes." ;
    pred:priority "high" ;
    rdfs:label "Arrange → page layout builder" ;
    pred:depends-on kb:graph-publishing ;
    pred:principle "Arranging nodes in a linear order, with vertical stacking and horizontal grouping, is exactly a page's block layout (sections, rows, columns). The graph-view arrange tools should translate DIRECTLY into web-page layout building — the same gesture that orders the graph orders the page." ;
    rdf:type <urn:kbase:type/Feature> ;
    pred:open-question "Where is the arrangement stored — extend nodeOrder + the hnav ordering predicates (urn:reckons:nav/order|layer) with a row/column grouping, or a dedicated layout predicate? It must round-trip to the page block model." ;
    pred:open-question "Full-screen vertical scroll implies a DOM/scroll surface, not the fixed canvas the other force modes use — is arrange a special non-canvas mode, or a canvas with virtual scroll? DOM makes the page-layout mapping far more direct." ;
    pred:feature-id "F60" ;
    pred:relates-to kb:publishing-v2 ;
    pred:has-status "speculative" .

